column9: TEXT
Good day, ladies and gentlemen, and welcome to the nine-month period 2013 Enersis earnings conference call.
My name is Lisa and I will be your operator for today.

These statements could include statements regarding the intent, belief, or current expectations of Enersis and its management with respect to, among other things, Enersis' business plans, Enersis' cost reduction plans, trends affecting Enersis' financial condition or results of operations including market trends in the electricity sector in Chile or otherwise, supervision and regulation of the electricity sector in Chile or otherwise and the future effects of any changes in the laws and regulation applicable to Enersis or its affiliates.

These factors include a decline in the equity capital markets of the United States or Chile, an increase in the market rates of interest in the United States or otherwise, adverse decisions by government regulators in Chile or otherwise and other factors described in Enersis' annual report Form 20-F, including under risk factors.
You may access our 20-F on the SEC's website, www.SEC.gov.
I would now like to turn the presentation over to Mr. Eduardo Escaffi, Enersis' CFO.
Please proceed.
Good morning, ladies and gentlemen, and welcome to our nine-month 2013 results presentation.
My name is Eduardo Escaffi, Enersis' Chief Financial Officer.
For the beginning let me remind you that our conference call will be conducted following a presentation that was -- that has been already uploaded on our website.
Today I am here with Pedro Canamero, Enersis' Investor Relations Director, and his team which will also be available to assist you with (inaudible) detailed information after this call.
Also as usual, I will take your calls -- your questions at the end of this presentation.
Now let's begin the presentation providing you some highlights for the period on slide number 2.
As of September attributable net income increased by 77% reaching about $1 billion and already represents close to 58% of total net income versus 42% in the same period last year.
That incremental contribution is mainly explained by the good performance of the EBITDA which increased by more than 12% up to $3.3 billion during the period.

This was mainly attained thanks to the positive results achieved after the hard regulatory efforts being performed by our regulatory division in Argentina, both in generation and in distribution, and a more efficient generation mix mainly in Chile.
And the in-kind contribution from our parent Company in Spain during the capital increase finalized during the first quarter of 2013.

In particular the positive EBITDA evolution was the result of the important contribution of our distribution business, which increased by almost 15% and continues to benefit from the growth of our customer base, expanding at a rate of more than 3% or 460,000 clients during the last 12 months, and our generation performance which increased by 11% compared to the same period last year, mainly thanks to the cost reduction linked to Bocamina II and the lower LNG cost in a year that continues being drier than the average.
Let's now analyze the business context during the period inside slide number 3.
As you can see in the upper part, electricity demand growth has been positive in all the countries in which we operate.
Bear in mind that this period has been influenced by the absence of fewer working days as well as mild temperatures.
Regarding the generation output, the improvement during the third quarter allowed us to recover the same levels we had last year, reaching 43 kilowatt hours.
This was mainly explained by higher thermal dispatch in Chile in turn mainly explained by Bocamina II, which has compensated lower hydro generation in the rest of the countries where we operate.

As far as the spot market, the situation did not change dramatically versus the first half of the year when Chile resisted lower energy prices in connection with a better mix and lower fuel costs related to higher thermal production at a more efficient cost.
While Colombia in Brazil revealed significant increases due to the lower hydro production during this period.
Let's continue with an overview of some relevant financial highlights in slide number 4.
Revenues decreased by 5% mainly due to regulatory change in Argentina which impacted both revenues and costs, thus not affecting EBITDA.
Excluding Argentina effect coming from the affirmation Resolution 95, revenues remained barely flat for the rest of the countries.
Costs decreased by about 13% mainly thanks to a more efficient generation mix mainly in Chile, together with lower costs in Argentina and Brazil.
As a result EBITDA amounted to $3.3 billion or higher -- 12% higher compared to last year.

This was mainly the result of the positive (inaudible) in Chile, Argentina and Peru, partially offset by the decreasing contribution of Brazil which has been affected by the exchange rate conversion from reals to Chilean pesos.

Net income attributable to shareholders amounted to about $1 billion, equivalent to a 77% increase compared to the same period last year, mainly thanks to the improvement in the Chilean generation business.

A (inaudible) regulation (inaudible) in generation and distribution in Argentina and the in-kind contribution that permitted the consolidation of certain companies in Enersis after the recent capital increase.
Now moving to slide number 5, the EBIT increased by about 13%, in-line with the EBITDA.
Our net financial expense amounted to $292 million, an improvement of about $190 million versus last year.

This improvement was mainly the result of higher financial income of about $150 million primarily as a result of the cash invested that was collected from the capital increase in the first quarter of 2013 as well as higher income in Edesur and, on the other hand, lower financial expenses of $50 million.
Our average cost of gross debt in nominal terms was 8.2% a year, a decrease compared to last year's of 8.9%.
This was mainly explained by a lower inflation rate in Chile and lower interest rates in the countries where we operate.
Finally, our aggregate effective tax rate was 29%, in line with the figure we registered in the same period last year.
Let's move to slide number 6 where regulation -- since regulation is a key consideration in the development of our activities, especially in our distribution business.

Regarding recent developments in Peru, let us highlight that on October 15 OSINERGMIN, the regulatory body in Peru, published Resolution 203 establishing the distribution tariffs for Edelnor, our distribution Company there, to be effective from November 13 to October 17.
Under this resolution the value added in distribution -- in distribution rate for our (inaudible) subsidiary increased by 1.2%.

In Brazil the latest regulatory changes meant a debt reduction of the energy remuneration in the country coming from the decision not to renew certain hydro concessions and the corresponding energy contracts together with a general lower hydro availability.

This generated a temporary imbalance between the supply and the demand of LNG in the system creating an involuntary exposure to the spot market for distribution companies when marginal prices were very high due to the prevailing drought.
We expect that these extra costs will be recognized in the following months from 2014 onwards.

In Chile, on October 14, the government passed the law 2025 promoting the development of nonconventional renewal energy services in the country's energy mix, stating that by 2025, 20% of the total output must be met by [the services].
Meanwhile, the electricity concession law passed on the same date is intended to facilitate the awarding of this (inaudible) concessions.

In Argentina Resolution 95 published in March 26, established a new regulatory framework for the electricity generation based on a scheme which bases fixed and variable costs plus an additional remuneration.
As a consequence you will not [list] a recurrent decrease in operating revenues and also an operating cost for our [thermal] subsidiary, Costanera, booking only the margin in this case.
I remind you that this measure was applied retroactively from February 2013.
Finally, let's recall that in Edesur, our Argentine distribution subsidiary, Enersis resisted a positive effect pursuant to resolution 2050 which we recognize historical cost retroactive to May 2007.
The latter resulted in increased EBITDA of $304 million and $313 million in higher net income.
Let's go to other countries in the region in slide number 7.
As you can see in the slide, nine months 2013 EBITDA in local currency increases in all the areas of presence, except in Brazil which remained fairly flat.
Let's go country by country starting with Chile in the slide number 8.
Despite the continuous and (inaudible) rainfall condition in Chile, the generation segment's EBITDA grew by 36%.
This was the result of a greater thermal dispatch cost by the commencement of operations at Bocamina II power plant and the lower cost of LNG which led to better margins.

In the distribution segment our operations registered a 1% increase in EBITDA, mainly due to lower energy revenues as a result of lower average sale prices following the Company's (inaudible) review in effect as of November 2012.
Electricity demand grew by 5% in our concession area while energy losses remained at 5.5%.
Let's move to our Brazilian operations on slide number 9.
Our Brazilian operations continue to face the effect of local currency depreciation, which represented a decline of 10% in the year-to-date results in Chilean pesos.
In order to illustrate the severe consequences arising from the exchange effect in Chile, let us mention that just during third quarter local currency depreciated 4% against Chilean peso.
Excluding this effect EBITDA in generation increased by about 2% mainly driven by an increase of -- by the Fortaleza plant due to a greater demand within the system.

Distribution produced an EBITDA decrease of about 2% mainly due to the effects of the drought affecting Brazil which increased energy costs incurred by distributors, increasing their exposure to the spot market.
These extra costs could not be [immediately] compensated through a regulatory mechanism and are expected to be recovered in future periods according to Brazilian regulation.
Ampla benefited from reduced procurement and services costs and the number of customers increased by 90,000, reaching 3 million clients.
Coelce [reduced] lower operating revenues due to a decline in average sale price following the tighter production that became effective in April 2012.

In addition, we [saved] the retroactive tariff decrease from April 2011 and to April 2012, more than offsetting a significant increase in physical sales and the reduction and procurement and services costs.
Let's now move to Colombia on slide number 10.
In the generation business EBITDA increased by more than 8% as better margins were only partially offset by lower output related to fewer rainfalls.
In particular the lower hydro generation compared to the same period of 2012 when heavy rainfalls were reduced in the country boosting output at the time.

Was partially offset by the higher thermal dispatch, especially from our coal-fired plant in [Mosipa], all the above was compensated by higher sales prices which more than balanced higher production costs from our thermal facilities.

Regarding our distribution business, Codensa [resisted] a slight increase of about 1% in demand, mainly explained by the lower economic activity in our concession area corresponding to (inaudible) city.
It is important to mention the significant improvement of energy losses which dropped from 7.6% to 7.2% thanks to the effort undertaken by the Company in order to mitigate this effect.
All in all EBITDA in this business segment remained flat.
Let's look at Peru on slide number 11.
In local currency the generation business slowed and -- showed an increase of 9% in the EBITDA.
This includes revenues from the Piura subsidiary, a Company that entered the consolidation of Enersis following the (inaudible) increase.
The latter was partially offset by reduced revenues in our subsidiary (inaudible) mainly as a result of a 7% fall in physical energy saves on the expiration of some regulated customer contracts.
Plus a reduction in the average energy sales price.
Distribution reported an increase of 11% in EBITDA, mainly explained by higher physical sales and other services, together with an improvement in Enersis losses which declined from 8.2% to 8.0%.
Let's now move to Argentina on slide number 12.

In generation EBITDA increased by 4% mainly explained by the increase in Costanera's margin, including the remuneration received by the combined cycle availability contract as a consequence of the aforementioned resolution Number 95.
As a consequence of it you will appreciate a recurring [increase] in operating revenues and also an operating cost of our thermal subsidiary.
Our hydro subsidiary (inaudible) in turn showed a lower operating performance mainly as a consequence of a fall in fiscal sales related to the low dispatch.

In distribution attributable EBITDA increased by around $295 million mainly reflecting the positive one time effect of (inaudible) in the second quarter of $384 million coming from the aforementioned regulatory effect in Edesur.
Let me remind you that on November 7 we'll begin the preemptive price offering for the capital increase of Costanera aimed to restore the capital base of our subsidiary.
Let's now move to the cash flow analysis on slide number 13.

In the first nine months of 2013 cash flow from operations amounted to $2.1 billion, this cash was fully employed during the [building] CapEx amount in $1.1 billion where 57% was invested in distribution and 43% in generation.
Dividends for $0.8 billion which we have paid during the first and the second quarter of this year and interest payments up to $0.2 billion.
All in all Enersis continues to show a strong financial position, our liquidity position amounts to about $4 billion and allows us to easily service the maturities throughout 2016.
Please refer to our annexes for further detail.
Thank you very much for your time and we can open Q&A session and hand over to the -- and hand over to the operator, Lisa, please.
(Operator Instructions).
Alexander.
Hi Eduardo, I have a question related to financial income this quarter.
In previous quarter we saw financial income of $180 million and this quarter about $100 million.
Why did we see this drop and how will financial incomes coming from capital increase funds were reflected again?

As you know, we received $2.3 billion in our capital increase in March and they are duly invested in Chilean pesos and they are an average of 5.6% in Chilean pesos that then you can have that $150 million roughly speaking.
And the other part of the financial expenses comes from less financial costs because of the lower interest rate that we are paying because of the lower inflation rate.
And also we have some -- the financial income that comes from Edesur also because -- with the resolution they paid the bills that they had with CAMMESA.
And that is why we have that very important increase in this financial expenses line.
(Inaudible) financial income have dropped and not unsimilar to those of one quarter.
And we expect that with (technical difficulty) from capital increase this line will climb.
Sorry, I couldn't hear you.
Please (inaudible) again.
In first quarter financial income were about $100 million.
In second quarter we see a higher level due to in part this Argentinean income.
But this quarter we saw levels similar to those of first quarter.
And there is no climb due to capital increase funds.
The capital increase funds, it represents roughly speaking $100 million in this period.
The Edesur comes in -- they arrive just in the second quarter.
But they are not recurrent.
We are going to see the other $100 million -- as I mentioned before, you will have to take in consideration the $2.3 million and the -- invested at 5.5%, 5.6% the year.
That is the recurring one.
Okay, thank you very much.
Z. Cole-Fernandes], Scopia Bank.
Congratulations on the results.
I want to ask you three questions.
First I want to know the EBITDA jump in third quarter for the Peruvian distribution unit, what was related to.
The second one, how do you expect to be the pace of recognition for your Brazilian distribution unit in terms of the higher costs due to the drought?

And the third one is what would you need to happen or what is missing for you to decide to make an offer for the minorities listed in other LatAm exchanges apart from Santiago like (inaudible) or (inaudible)?
Thank you very much.
Well let's begin with the distribution (technical difficulty).

As you know, the -- our Companies were impacted because there was the perfect storm coming, the Companies had to go to the spot market in the moment in which the spot market was -- the prices were very, very high.
The regulator recognized that part -- some part this year and some part is going to be recognized next year.
And we expect that we are going to recover all the difference during the next year.
Then we recognize roughly half of the cost this year.
And if you take in consideration what is happening with our Companies, Coelce and Ampla, they are less affected than our peers.

In a way the regulator is very worried about the situation of other companies if you take in consideration the financial health of electro (inaudible) companies, so they are in a very -- well, with some problems.
Then in a way we expect that the regulation is going to comply with the recovery of the extra cost that we had in this involuntary portion to the spot market.
In terms of the minorities -- minority interest on the other M&A operations that we are going to -- that is our target in order to -- stated target for our capital increase.
The use of funds of our capital increase.
As you can imagine, if we say that we are going to go after one company the price of those shares are going to jump [linearly].
That is exactly what happened immediately after the announcement of the capital increase.

At one -- at some point the prices of some of the shares that are the natural targets of our Company jumped up to almost 60% above the undisturbed price and now all of them have been descending to more, quote, (inaudible) levels.
Then it is very important for you as investor that we have to act in a very responsible way and not to be stating which are the targets and how we are going to do.
Then I ask you to be patient as we have been.
And this patience has brought lots of results in terms of today our purchasing power is almost 20% higher than the one that we had after the capital increase ended.
And sorry, the distribution or the --.
(Inaudible - microphone inaccessible).
Sorry about that.
Your first question about how -- why the distribution was so -- it jumped 50%.
Well, most of that situation is attributable to our Edesur one time effect.
That the government regulator recognized the extra cost that -- our Company was.
Not our Company, only our Company, but also the rest of the sector, the rest of our peers had since 2007 recognized the extra cost that we had.
That is related to the resolution to 150 that was in May -- approved in May.
And that is a one-time affect.
We are -- and it is very interesting because even though it seems that it has no cash flow effect.
It does have, because with that they recognize that some debts that we already had with CAMMESA they were compensated with that recognition.
Since we are ones of those companies that we pay our bills that money is not going to go out of the Company.
Then that affects, as I mentioned before, it was $380 million one-time effect was the most important effect that explains that 50%.
Otherwise our distribution and distribution site had been behaving as a distribution business should be.

A very stable cost conscious business in which we are able to extract value from reducing losses and a growing base of customers that comes into our business as the economists are growing at let's say 5% -- from 4% to 5% a year.
Okay, thank you very much.
Charles Fishman, Morningstar.
The tariff increase in Peru will -- it is just a 1.2% revenue increase, am I reading that properly?
Yes, this is the VAD, the Valor Agregado de Distribucion, that is the value added, the -- is a short explanation.

We every four to five years we enter into a discussion with the regulator and the tariff revision in which the regulator looks after which are the asset bases that we have to have in order to bring to our customers a service that is intended in terms of the regulatory framework.

After that discussion they remunerate us and in this case in consideration of the latest tariff that we had we had a 1.2% increase, that is mainly based on the asset base and that we were able to show that it is needed in order to give the service that is required in our concession area.
That will represent roughly speaking $2.5 million per year of extra EBITDA.
[Ivan Vunig], [CHG].
My questions were with the distribution companies in Brazil.
I would like to know around the amount these extra costs have been reduced in this year.
Like how much of these costs are going to be in the total year?
Right.
Roughly speaking we are talking about $65 million next year.
That's roughly speaking; please this needs a more precise calculation.
But roughly speaking $65 million was the amount of tariff review that -- of extra cost that has to be incorporated in tariff next year.
(Operator Instructions).
[Alex Virgil], [Senadis].
Hello, Alejandro Vigil from Cygnus Asset Management.
Just, Eduardo, a question about the outlook for the next quarter and for next year.
Looking particularly to consensus numbers, there is a very wide range of estimates, probably in the range of 30% from bottom to top.
If you can help us to understand the key trends for Enersis looking into next year.
Well, as you know, we don't give forecasts, but in terms of the main driver for generation hydro is the key issue.
But as you saw this year, even though we are experiencing a very dry condition almost very similar to this year, we were able to extract value from the generation mix.
That is the cost of producing with coal and our LNG contract provides us a very interesting margin.
That if conditions are similar to next year it is reasonable to think that we can extract the same value.
But if the condition, the hydro condition resumes to long-term trends that means that we can have a normal year.
Currently I have to remember you that currently we have a supply, a surplus probability of 75%, 72%, that is rather dry.
But if we go to a 50% we are going to replace those even cheap by another standards generation costs of coal and gas by water that is even cheaper.
Then the margin can improve dramatically.
That is what we can expect in Chile in terms of generation.
That same can be said in the other countries in which we are.
But in terms of distribution you can't find dramatic changes.
As I mentioned before, the bid distribution -- the only dramatic change (inaudible) that you are going to find at that probably we are not going to have -- find again the Edesur one-time effect.
But since you see that we are pursuing reducing costs, reducing losses, our distribution basis growing, you can see that the growth is sustained over time.
But we don't see dramatic changes over time.
All right, thank you.
There are no additional questions.
I would now like to turn the presentation back over to Mr. Eduardo Escaffi.
Well, since there are no more questions I would like to thank you all for your time and attention.
Remember that our Investor Relations team will be glad to assist you in any further questions you may have.
Have a nice afternoon and goodbye.
This concludes the presentation.
You may now disconnect.
Have a great day.
